{"Citation":{"eType":"journal","sVol":"50","sPage":"30-6","dateCit":"2020-09-29","sPubName":"J. Chem. Thermodyn.","yrPubYr":"2012","sAuthor":["Miranda, M. S.[Margarida S.]","Matos, M. A. R.[M. Agostinha R.]","Morais, V. M. F.[Victor M. F.]","Liebman, J. F.[Joel F.]"],"sKeyword":["2,1,3-benzothiadiazole","Enthalpy","Combustion","Sublimation","G3(MP2)//B3LYP","Structure","Aromaticity."],"tml_elements":["TRCRefID","eType","eSourceType","sAuthor","sPubName","yrPubYr","dateCit","sTitle","sAbstract","sKeyword","sDOI","sVol","sPage"],"sDOI":"10.1016/j.jct.2012.02.005","sTitle":"2,1,3-Benzothiadiazole: study of its structure, energetics and aromaticity","TRCRefID":{"yrYrPub":"2012","sAuthor1":"mir","sAuthor2":"mat","tml_elements":["yrYrPub","sAuthor1","sAuthor2","nAuthorn"],"nAuthorn":"0"},"sAbstract":"The present work reports an experimental study on the energetics of 2,1,3-benzothiadiazole and a computational study on its structure, energetics and aromaticity. In the experimental part the standard (p=0.1 MPa) massic energy of combustion, at T=298.15K, was measured by rotating bomb combustion calorimetry, in oxygen, and allowed the calculation of the respective standard molar enthalpy of formation, in the crystalline phase, at T = 298.15 K. The standard molar enthalpy of sublimation, at T = 298.15 K, was measured by high-temperature Calvet microcalorimetry. From the combination of data obtained by both techniques we were able to calculate the respective standard molar enthalpy of formation, in the gas phase, at T = 298.15 K: (276.6 +- 2.5) kJ mol-1. This  thermochemical parameter was compared with estimates obtained from high level ab initio quantum chemical calculations using the G3(MP2)//B3LYP composite method and various appropriately chosen reactions. The molecular structure of 2,1,3-benzothiadiazole was obtained from DFT calculations with the B3LYP density functional and various basis sets: 6-31G(d), 6-311(d,p), 6-311+G(3df,2p), augccpVTZ  and aug-ccpVQZ and its aromaticity and that of some related molecules were evaluated by analysis of nucleus independent chemical shifts (NICS) values.","eSourceType":"Original"},"Version":{"nVersionMajor":2,"nVersionMinor":0,"tml_elements":["nVersionMajor","nVersionMinor"]},"THERMOML_MD5_CHECKSUM":"e0114908a9ab474ac27e59ad4cd2f9eb","Compound":[{"RegNum":{"tml_elements":["nOrgNum"],"nOrgNum":1},"sStandardInChI":"InChI=1S/H2O4S/c1-5(2,3)4/h(H2,1,2,3,4)","sFormulaMolec":"H2O4S","sStandardInChIKey":"QAOWNCQODCNURD-UHFFFAOYSA-N","sCommonName":["sulfuric acid"],"tml_elements":["RegNum","sStandardInChI","sStandardInChIKey","sCommonName","sFormulaMolec"]},{"sStandardInChIKey":"CURLTUGMZLYLDI-UHFFFAOYSA-N","RegNum":{"tml_elements":["nOrgNum"],"nOrgNum":2},"sStandardInChI":"InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3","sCommonName":["carbon dioxide"],"tml_elements":["RegNum","sStandardInChI","sStandardInChIKey","sCommonName","sFormulaMolec"],"sFormulaMolec":"CO2"},{"sCommonName":["nitrogen"],"tml_elements":["RegNum","sStandardInChI","sStandardInChIKey","sCommonName","sFormulaMolec"],"sFormulaMolec":"N2","sStandardInChIKey":"IJGRMHOSHXDMSA-UHFFFAOYSA-N","sStandardInChI":"InChI=1S/N2/c1-2","RegNum":{"tml_elements":["nOrgNum"],"nOrgNum":3}},{"sStandardInChIKey":"XLYOFNOQVPJJNP-UHFFFAOYSA-N","RegNum":{"nOrgNum":4,"tml_elements":["nOrgNum"]},"sStandardInChI":"InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2","sFormulaMolec":"H2O","sCommonName":["water"],"tml_elements":["RegNum","sStandardInChI","sStandardInChIKey","sCommonName","sFormulaMolec"]},{"tml_elements":["RegNum","sStandardInChI","sStandardInChIKey","sCommonName","sFormulaMolec"],"sCommonName":["oxygen"],"sFormulaMolec":"O2","sStandardInChIKey":"MYMOFIZGZYHOMD-UHFFFAOYSA-N","RegNum":{"nOrgNum":5,"tml_elements":["nOrgNum"]},"sStandardInChI":"InChI=1S/O2/c1-2"},{"sStandardInChI":"InChI=1S/C6H4N2S/c1-2-4-6-5(3-1)7-9-8-6/h1-4H","RegNum":{"tml_elements":["nOrgNum"],"nOrgNum":6},"sStandardInChIKey":"PDQRQJVPEFGVRK-UHFFFAOYSA-N","sFormulaMolec":"C6H4N2S","Sample":[{"eSource":"Commercial source","nSampleNm":1,"p